article.description: Heather Ezell scored 25 points as Iowa State (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) pounded Texas A&M (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) 67-50 Wednesday night, handing the Aggies their worst loss of the season.
article.headline: Cyclones remain perfect at home with upset of Aggies
article.linkText: Upstart Iowa State hammers No. 4 Texas A&M
article.story:
AMES, Iowa -- It was so odd to see Heather Ezell miss a 3-pointer that even she had to laugh.

By then, Ezell could afford to smile. She had already done more than enough to give Iowa State (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) one of its biggest wins in years.

Ezell scored a season-high 25 points -- burying four straight 3s to open the second half -- as the Cyclones pounded Texas A&M (No. 4 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) 67-50 Wednesday night and handed the Aggies their worst loss of the season.

Texas A&M entered play ranked second in the nation in 3-point percentage defense, but that didn't faze Ezell.

She went 7-of-13 from 3-point range and hit five 3s in the second half, helping the Cyclones build an insurmountable lead.

The win was Iowa State's first over a top 10 team since it knocked off then-No. 2 Texas Tech 64-63 on Jan. 14, 2004. The Cyclones have beaten two straight ranked opponents, having taken down Kansas State (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP) 60-50 on Saturday.

"Certainly a win, hopefully, that our kids can embrace and build on," Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly said. "When you have back-to-back wins against ranked teams, it helps in a lot of ways."

Takia Starks scored 18 points to lead the Aggies (17-4, 5-3), who had won their last two road games against ranked opponents. But any hopes Texas A&M had of cutting a 12-point deficit down to a manageable number early in the second half were squashed by Ezell.

She opened the half with a 3 and a pair of free throws to put Iowa State ahead 38-23. The Aggies hit a pair of quick baskets to pull back within 11, but Ezell answered with two straight 3s to put the Cyclones ahead by 17.

Ezell's final 3 of that stretch was a thing of beauty. With her back to the basket and the shot clock about to expire, Ezell flipped around and tossed the ball into the rim with one hand, giving Iowa State a 47-27 lead.

"She is ultimately confident, in a good way," Fennelly said. "She doesn't care. If she's open, she's going to pull the trigger."

Ezell finally missed a long one on her next trip down the floor, and could little but laugh as she ran back on defense. Though Texas A&M went on a 7-2 run to throw a brief scare into Iowa State, Ezell drained a 3 from the elbow to make it 57-36 just over 8 minutes left.

"It was just one of those games where you're getting lucky, things are going in, shots are falling," Ezell said.

Ezell's heroics might sealed the win for the Cyclones, but the truth was the Aggies were never really in the game anyway.

Iowa State held Texas A&M to just 10 points in the opening 13:40, grabbed 20 of the game's first 26 rebounds and built a 19-10 lead. The Cyclones jumped ahead 30-18 as Amanda Nisleit followed a 3 with back-to-back layups, and Alison Lacey's running 3 at the first-half buzzer gave Iowa State a 33-21 lead.

"It's not the 3s that beat us by Ezell, because she was just hot," Texas A&M Gary Blair said. "They beat us with the execution of all [their] other players."

Though the Cyclones shot just 37.5 percent from the field in the first half, they beat the Aggies 11-0 on the offensive glass and scored 12 second-chance points.

"We had some kids lay down on us today, and I've never had that happen before," said Blair, who is in his sixth season in College Station.

Texas A&M opened the season at 14-1 before losing to back-to-back games against Oklahoma and Baylor. The Aggies appeared to have turned things around with wins at Oklahoma State and No. 16 Texas, but this was an alarming setback for a team that entered play tied for second in the brutal Big 12.

Texas A&M's biggest loss before Wednesday night was a 12-point setback to the Sooners in Norman.

"Some of us just quit. As a team -- I've never played on a team where people just quit," Starks said. "Just really not happy with our effort tonight."

The lone bright spot for the Aggies was Starks, who set Texas A&M's career record for 3s with 12:38 left in the first half. Starks, the cousin of former NBA star John Starks, broke the mark of 165 career 3-pointers set by former All-American Lisa Branch from 1992-96.

No other Aggie had more than six points.

As good as Ezell was from long range against Texas A&M, she didn't come close to her career record for 3s. She hit 10 3s against Sacramento State in 2007.

"We've still got a lot of season left," Ezell said. "The highlight of our season doesn't want to be beating Texas A&M here at home. We want to do some other things."
